🌱 Prologue: The "Audacity" and Dreams of Freshmen
In early 2025, five freshmen from the School of Electronic Information Engineering at CQUPT formed the "Zero Point" team. Brought together by our school's project opportunities and a shared interest in quantum computing under the guidance of our mentor, we had never even touched an HPC cluster, let alone understood Einstein's field equations or CUDA programming.
When we saw the ASC26 competition topics, our instinct told us this would be an extreme test of translating theory into engineering. The competition offered two seemingly unrelated tracks:
Track A: Optimize the Unitree robot world model (GPU/AI direction).
Track B: Optimize the AMSS-NCKU gravitational-wave simulation (CPU/HPC direction).
Our mentor initially gave us a reality check: "Let's be clear: this first year is just for practice. We'll participate every year, aiming to win a prize in our junior or senior year." But eager to seize the opportunity, we made a bold decision: compete in both tracks simultaneously. This was not just a test of our technical skills, but an experiment to see how much value a "zero-experience" team could create. Our motto: "From Zero, Everything is Possible."
🤖 Track A: A 7.77× Speedup in Robot "Mental Rehearsal"
Lead: Team Collaboration (AI Optimization Group)
Core Achievement: Inference time reduced from 588 seconds (nearly 10 minutes) to 75.68 seconds, achieving a 7.77× speedup.
1. The Dilemma: Optimization Space Locked by Rules
Unitree's UniFM-WMA-0 model is responsible for the robot's "mental rehearsal" (video prediction). Initial tests were disheartening: a single sample took nearly 10 minutes to infer. To make matters worse, the competition rules strictly prohibited modifying core files or using quantization below 16-bit. We had to find a way to survive in the cracks.
2. The Breakthrough: A Six-Layer Optimization "Combo"
Instead of relying on a single silver bullet, we used systematic engineering to stack six complementary optimizations, like building blocks:
