🌌 Track B: Solitude and Epiphanies in Gravitational-Wave Simulation
Lead: Task B Specialist (Personal Perspective)
Core Achievement: Simulation speed increased by 2.59×, reducing the time for a 1000-second physical simulation from an estimated 157 hours to 32.8 hours.
1. The Darkest Hour: Environment Setup "Dropout"
When we received the topic, I was completely overwhelmed by Einstein's field equations and Adaptive Mesh Refinement (AMR). The real blow came from setting up the environment:
The university's supercomputer was outdated, running only GCC 4.8.5, unsupported by many modern libraries.
We needed to statically compile Python 3.8.18, and the supercomputer had no internet access.
The Breaking Point: I downloaded packages on a virtual machine and transferred them via scp, only to be constantly plagued by libgfortran version mismatches and MATLAB library paths polluting environment variables.
The Breakthrough: After two days of relentless troubleshooting—uninstalling conflicting libraries, manually setting LD_LIBRARY_PATH, and using rpath to hardcode library paths into executables—I finally ran the first "Hello World." This experience gave me a transformative understanding of Linux internals.
2. Exploration: Finding the 16-Core "Sweet Spot"
During benchmark testing, I discovered a counterintuitive phenomenon: more cores are not always better.
4 cores took 120 minutes to simulate 10 seconds of physical time.
When I tested 24 cores, performance was actually worse than 16 cores!
The Epiphany: Research revealed this was due to memory bandwidth saturation. The growth in communication overhead canceled out parallelization gains. This was my first true understanding of the "boundaries of parallel computing."
3. Failure: The CSAMR Algorithm "Waterloo"
In pursuit of ultimate performance, I spent a week studying a 2016 top-tier conference paper, attempting to implement the CSAMR (Concurrent Adaptive Mesh Refinement) algorithm.
The Disaster: After modifying the code and running a test, it only advanced 0.7 seconds of physical time per hour (the original algorithm did 1 second).
The Reflection: CSAMR requires all levels to use the finest level's time step, causing an exponential explosion in coarse grid computation. This algorithm needs a massive 128+ core cluster to shine. With our limited 16-core resources, the classic Time-subcycling approach was the true king.
The Takeaway: This failure taught me that "advanced" does not equal "applicable." Algorithms must match the hardware scale.
4. The Surprise: The Unexpected Joy of -flto
After trying -O3 (which slowed things down) and MKL (which caused performance regression), I casually tried Link Time Optimization (-flto).
The Miracle: Adding just this single parameter boosted performance by about 7% (50.33 min → 46.8 min).
In that moment, I felt all the previous errors and sleepless nights were worth it.
5. The Wait: 32.8 Hours of Agony
Finally, I submitted the full 1000-second simulation job. For two days, I refreshed qstat constantly, watching the progress bar inch forward like waiting for exam results. When I finally saw Total Time: 118170s and the constraint graphs perfectly met the standards, the sense of accomplishment was beyond words.
💡 Conclusion: Failure is the Stepping Stone to Success
We are incredibly honored to be recognized with the National 2nd Prize. I remember the results came out in February. I was sitting in a physics class that evening, casually browsing the list of winning teams with a calm mind, when I suddenly spotted a familiar name: ASC1548. That was us. Although we didn't make it to the finals, the result far exceeded our expectations and was truly delightful. We hope to break into the finals in the coming year!!!
